article.description: Elton Brand and Jeff McInnis scored 20  points apiece and Darius Miles added 18 to lead the Los Angeles  Clippers to their third straight victory, a 109-95 triumph over  the Golden State Warriors.
article.headline: Clippers move to 2.5 games out of playoffs
article.linkText: Balanced Clippers trip Warriors for third straight win
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- The Los Angeles Clippers keep getting plenty of offense from reserves Darius Miles and Quentin Richardson.
Miles

Neither one of them wants to be a starter, either. Jeff McInnis had 20 points and 13 assists Saturday night in the Clippers' 109-95 victory over the Golden State Warriors. But it was Miles' athleticism that secured the victory, as he scored 12 of his 18 points in the fourth quarter. "Darius is going to be a starter sooner or later. But for this team right now, he is effective coming off the bench because we've got guys who can score with the starting group," McInnis said. "So when he and Q get in the game, it's almost better for them." Elton Brand added 20 points and 12 rebounds for the Clippers, who have won 14 of their last 21 meetings with the Warriors. Richardson had 17 points after getting into early foul trouble. The win pulled Los Angles within 2½ games of Seattle for the eighth and final Western Conference playoff spot. The victory also assured the Clippers of consecutive winning seasons at home for the first time since capping a three-year run in 1992-93. They are 21-10 at Staples Center after going 22-19 last season. Antawn Jamison had 24 points and 11 rebounds for the Warriors, who lost for the 28th time in 32 games and the 12th straight time on the road. Danny Fortson had 18 points and 11 boards. Coming off their first winning road trip of the season (3-2) and playing Golden State for the first time since an overtime loss in their home opener, the Clippers took a three-point lead into the fourth quarter and extended it to 95-84 with an 18-10 spurt fueled by Miles. The second-year forward made his first six shots of the period, four medium-range jumpers followed by a pair of slam dunks off alley-oop feeds from McInnis. "I saw Antawn backing off me a lot and I was able to get wide open a lot," Miles said. "So instead of going to the basket where people would be around me, I just wanted to spot up a couple of times, and everything worked." The second alley-oop was a result of sheer hustle by the 20-year-old Miles, who outhustled Jamison to a loose ball at midcourt that appeared to be bouncing over the scorer's table. But Miles kept it in play and flung it to McInnis, whose return pass found Miles soaring above the rim again with 6½ minutes left. "I've been kind of bad on the alley-oops lately in the last couple of games, so I just wanted to give him that one," McInnis said. "It was a hard decision who to give it to, but Darius worked the hardest to save it. It turned the game around." One night after the Warriors lost first-round draft pick Jason Richardson to a sprained left ankle, starting guard Larry Hughes sat out the final 13½ minutes of the first half after spraining his left ankle. Hughes started the second half after getting his ankle retaped, but did not take a shot in the third quarter as the Clippers extended their lead to nine points on Eric Piatkowski's 3-pointer with 7:34 left in the period. "They executed their offense, and we didn't do a good job of the same," Jamison said. "They got the lead and stayed poised." Earl Boykins' 21-footer in the final three seconds of the first half gave Los Angeles a 54-48 lead. Brand had 11 points and seven rebounds in the half, and Sean Rooks' 18-footer regained the lead for the Clippers at 44-43 with 3:12 left in the second quarter. Reserve guard Bob Sura gave the Warriors a momentary spark after Hughes limped off, scoring nine points during a two-minute span as the Warriors went on a 13-2 run that helped turn a seven-point deficit into a 39-35 lead with 4:40 left in the half. Sura finished with 15 points and 10 assists.

Game notes
Saturday was the 40th anniversary of Wilt Chamberlain's 100-point game for the then-Philadelphia Warriors, against the New York Knicks at Hershey, Pa. ... Sunday is the 36th anniversary of Chamberlain's 62-point game against the Warriors -- the second-highest total ever by a Warriors opponent. Current Clippers general manager Elgin Baylor scored 63 points against them for Boston in a triple-overtime game. ... The Clippers franchise has made the playoffs six times in its 32-year history, including three times in Los Angeles -- but never in a season in which they had a losing streak longer than six games. Their longest skid so far this season is four. ... The Warriors are 8-26 since Brian Winters replaced Dave Cowens as coach on Dec. 15.
